{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:18:24.410Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing User Requirements**\n\nI've zeroed in on the core of the user request. My focus is now on meticulously dissecting the requirements. I am now centered on connecting route guards to backend authentication and RBAC, particularly integrating the `/auth/` endpoint. The 'phase5-frontend-integration' scope and the restriction on landing page changes are also critical factors for consideration. I am now mapping the 'update private route guards' task to the authentication backend.\n\n\n**Refining Route Guard Logic**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the logic within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. I need to ensure it correctly handles both `/portal` and `/admin` routes. My immediate goal is integrating the backend auth state from `/auth/me` with the stored MVP token (`gff_ai_access_token`). I'm currently working to determine the best approach for verifying session and token presence upon route guard mounting to prevent unintended redirection. I will address hydration safety and redirect loops during integration and testing.\n\n\n**Designing Authentication Flow**\n\nI'm now designing the authentication flow within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. If a token exists in local storage, I plan to verify it by fetching `/api/v1/auth/me`. A successful response will update the session state, storing it under `gff_ai_preview_session_v1`. In cases of missing or invalid tokens, I'll leverage a phase 4 preview session as a fallback, following the logic and conditions outlined earlier.\n\n\n**Clarifying Access Rules**\n\nI am now clarifying access rules and redirection logic. With no token or session, users will go to `/portal/login` or see a \"Sign-in required\" message. I am now refining the routing to handle role-based access to `/portal` and `/admin` routes. Client roles can access `/portal` only, while admin roles access `/admin` only. A forbidden role access will display an \"Access Restricted\" page.\n\n\n**Revising Access Control**\n\nI am now revising access control rules, specifically focusing on `/portal` and `/admin` routes. I need to ensure client roles are limited to `/portal` while admin roles are restricted to `/admin`. The existing code allowed admin access to `/portal` too. I am ensuring that unauthorized attempts to access `/admin` by client roles display the intended \"Access Restricted\" page. I will revisit existing logic to ensure it adheres to the updated access control specifications.\n\n\n"}}
